Multiple sclerosis: It is not only about the medication, but also about the patient’s will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: neurologist, physiotherapist, occupational therapist, urologist, ophthalmologist, psychologist, psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not only a matter of medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultations, if they decide to have a child, social legal advice, recommendations for housing adjustment, etc., are part of the care for these patients.
Yet all this is not enough: the development of the disease can significantly affect the patient himself.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and does not have to fundamentally change the style of his life.
As doctors point out, the passivity of the sick frees up space for disease activity.
For example, regular movement has been shown to significantly delay the time when the patient needs some compensatory aid, such as a stick.
It is important that patients and their surroundings do not succumb to various myths, for example, that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
This is why the website Give a Chance (www.bezmytu.cz) was created, which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give a Chance.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
For multiple sclerosis, there is a double rule that the sooner the disease is treated, the more the doctor can influence something.
This is because we have drugs for multiple sclerosis at an inflammatory stage, when the process of neurodegeneration is not yet so strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the hope that we will succeed in stopping the disease and delaying the disability, explains Dr. Eva Medov<0xC3><0xA1> from the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
It is very important in people with multiple sclerosis rehabilitation care, which most often resolves the weakening of the lower extremities or imbalance.
We work with patients according to their individual needs: to maintain their condition, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, relieve swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It's really individual, it depends on the specific problems of the patient," says Dr. Martina K<0xC3><0xB6>v<0xC3><0xA1>ri, the primary care physician of the Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine Clinic of the Faculty Hospital in Motol.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but it manifests itself in a slightly different way for everyone.
Rehabilitation cannot stop the disease, but it can always alleviate its symptoms.
However, movement activity also strengthens the immune state of the body, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive aspect of regular exercise is the fact that patients check what they can do, and this strengthens their self-confidence.
"Endorphins also wash out during the exercise and one feels good after it," says Dr. Kamila <0xC5><0x98>asov<0xC3><0xA1> from the Clinic of Rehabilitation Medicine at the Royal Vinohrady University Hospital.
By influencing the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
We intervene directly in the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, he adds.
"In the past, these patients were so-called saved, today we know that they need a targeted load," says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kol<0xC3><0xA1><0xC5><0x99>, head of the Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine Clinic of the Faculty Hospital in Motol.
The goal of physiotherapy is to allow a person to remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including work placement.
Physiotherapists therefore cooperate with occupational therapists, so that each person gets a compensation aid tailored to him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They are in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most people shake it.
They experience shock, panic, fear.
It must respond to a great burden - the loss of health.
With such a sick soul, we have to follow someone, not try to take everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them to finally conclude that even with a disability one can live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinov<0xC3><0xA1> - Schubertov<0xC3><0xA1> from the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
