At their most anticipated meeting in years, federal reserve lawmakers will spend two days this week sitting at a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table and will decide whether it is time to raise the key interest rate after nearly a decade.
Standing above them at one end of the central bank ornament, the two-story meeting room will be a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed President Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are supposed to put the nation’s economic interests above everything else.
The central bank has a double charge from Congress: maximizing U.S. employment and keeping prices stable there.
But since the Great Recession, the Fed has recognized that there is an unwritten third term of office: financial stability.
And this third term could be an X-factor in too close to the predictable decision to be announced on Thursday on whether the U.S. economy is ready to kick-start as it pulls out of an unprecedented stimulus in the form of near-zero short-term interest rates on the ground since 2008.
Although most of the data shows solid economic growth, the recent turbulence in global financial markets could already scare the cautious Fed into adding to the volatility by raising its benchmark rate of federal funds – by nothing more than a quarter of a percentage point.
“It’s clear that the labour market and inflation will be, first and foremost, the most important thing to watch,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think they were just looking for an excuse to not raise the level, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already provides them with sufficient justification to wait," she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is causing nervousness in the financial markets.
About half of the economists surveyed recently by Blomberg predicted an increase in the rate this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to delay the matter, with a key indicator of only about a 30% chance of an increase.
This would point to a decline in the stock market if the Fed were to raise rates, only if politicians softened the decline by promising that further increases would be unnoticeable.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The meeting was launched on the expectation that Fed policymakers would hold rates back this week, says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the Fed were to raise rates now," he said.
If the Fed’s policy makers did this, “they would have to go to the extreme in their program statement and hold the financial markets in their hands so as not to panic.”
Other experts argued that raising rates would calm financial markets, as it would remove uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage point this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. economic recovery.
Yellen said she expects interest rates to rise this year through the spring and early summer, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the labor market has seen solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% in the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed considers full employment.
Wage gains showed signs of upswing.
And while inflation is still below the central bank’s annual 2% target, Fed policymakers say the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tightness of the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to slide late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell as much as 16% below its record value in May, as investors worried that China’s slowing economy would drag down global growth.
The market has rebounded somewhat this month and the Dow is now losing only nearly 10% of its May high.
The Fed’s political turmoil in the market provides a comprehensive calculation of when to start raising interest rates.
“In the absence of what has happened in the financial markets, and reports of the weakness of the Chinese economy in the last few weeks, there would be tightening at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
It now predicts that they will wait at least a month to gain better control over the consequences.
"There's a lot of uncertainty about the impact this will have on the U.S. economy, and they have almost no data to rely on about the latest developments in China," Oliner said.
The health status of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s main interests, so technically it should not be included in their decision-making.
But in fact, the Fed has become the currency authority of the entire world.
The influence of the central bank in recent years has been enormous.
A mere hint by then-President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “suspend” their monetary expansion into the market has triggered convulsions around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interconnected, Fed officials can be expected to follow developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central bankers and experts to better read the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global wealth-management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., noted this month that the “Fed has a history of over-the-top movements in financial markets that seem unrelated to economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee’s policy-making who pushed for rate increases, cited the 1998-99 decision as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to lower its benchmark rate by 0.75 percentage points during three sessions "despite limited identifiable growth impacts in the U.S.," Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed reversed these cuts.
The Fed should prioritize financial stability concerns only during a major crisis, such as the 2008 market crash, said Adam Posen S., a former member of the rate-setting committee at the Bank of England.
The latest wave is not even approaching this level, he said.
“You certainly don’t want to be in a situation of fear of rising rates because the markets are getting angry,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has a double mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don't think they should get to the top.
