For mildly obese diabetics, weight loss surgery could be useful
The benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes can last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to say whether mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those who are provided with nonsurgical treatment.
“Death rates take a long time to figure out,” says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert on weight loss surgery who wrote an introduction to the new study of JAMA surgery.
Surgery for weight loss, bariatric surgery are used to reduce the stomach by various methods.
Reducing hunger and limiting the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven to be effective for the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most of the research was done on people with morbid obesity with a body weight index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
BMI, which measures the weight-to-height ratio, is considered normal at values between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates a person’s overweight and people with a value above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new study, researchers from the Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected from a 2007 study that looked at two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrectomy - in type 3 diabetes treatment procedures in people who were slightly obese.
The average BMI among those who underwent surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year, according to a study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who were not provided with surgical treatment for diabetes remained roughly the same at 29.
Among patients with surgery, diabetes was completely resolved in 36 percent and partially in 28 cases.
In the treatment group, only 1 percent and partially only about 2 percent of patients were completely resolved for the comparison of diabetes.
Furthermore, control of blood pressure, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol was shown to be “generally better in the surgical group,” the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient’s blood hemoglobin A1c levels, which reflects the body’s ongoing blood sugar levels.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 percent, researchers say.
After surgery, the average haemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
In the treatment group, however, this value remained at about 8 percent.
But this better “glycemic control” — which is reflected in better A1c hemoglobin levels — did not reduce mortality at five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results with two types of surgery.
After the fifth year, the bypass group lost more weight compared to the gastrectomy group (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), achieved greater decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent versus 2.1 percent) and were more likely to have diabetes remission (46.9 percent versus 16.7 percent).
While the new study shows no improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden where they found that surgery leads to prolongation of life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29 percent more likely to survive the next 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not show an improvement in survival among post-surgery patients, according to Blackstone, it is a calming result for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in these procedures.
"Right here, this work is critical because it states that surgery is safer in a group with a lower BMI," without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone further claims that people and their doctors should start taking weight really seriously after the patient’s BMI drops between 27 and 30.
“I think we’ve been waiting too long to show people the seriousness of the situation,” he says.
